A '''Byssoid lichen'''<ref>"Byssoid" means "flax-like" or "silk-like", from the Greek ''βύσσος'' (f.), ''flax'' (''Linum angustifolium'', ''Linum usitatissimum''), Indian cotton (''Gossypium herbaceum''), silk; Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott, Henry Stuart Jones, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'', 9th edition, Clarendon Press, Oxford, 1940, p. 334</ref> is a [[lichen]] with a wispy growth form, having the appearance of [[teased wool]].<ref name=WIL/> ''[[Coenogonium|Coenogonium implexum]]'' is a byssoid lichen.<ref name=WIL>What is a lichen?, Australian National Botanical Garden, [https://www.anbg.gov.au/lichen/what-is-lichen.html]</ref>

Byssoid lichens are of two types, those where the cottony structure is dominated by photobiont filaments (e.g., ''[[Trentepohlia (alga)|Trentepohlia]]''), and those where fungal [[hyphae]] make up the cottony form, with the hyphae having typically [[wikt:Special:Search/coccoid|coccoid]] photobionts among them.<ref>A NEW BYSSOID LICHEN GENUS FROM TASMANIA, Gintaras KANTVILAS, Lichenologist 28(3): 229–237 (1996), [http://nhm2.uio.no/botanisk/lav/RLL/PDF2/Lichenologist/28/28_229-237.pdf]</ref>

